<paragraph blockId="5.[160,1155,470,566]" box="[160,294,470,496]" pageId="5" pageNumber="2940">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,294,470,496]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="2940">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[160,1155,470,566]" pageId="5" pageNumber="2940">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,362,505,531]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="2940">External capsule.</emphasis>
Approximately cylindrical; translucent, light brown or white; texture like a malleable fine paper. An extremity attached to the substratum for silken threads.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[160,1155,620,819]" pageId="5" pageNumber="2940">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,357,620,646]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="2940">Internal capsule.</emphasis>
Approximately cylindrical, broader sub-apically, tapering towards the extremities; basal and apical portions rounded; 
<quantity box="[711,793,656,681]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" pageId="5" pageNumber="2940" unit="mm" value="27.0">27 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[869,937,656,681]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="2940" unit="mm" value="9.0">9 mm</quantity>
wide; texture very brittle; dark brown, external surface opaque, internal one brilliant; a dense layer of light brown felt-like silk firmly attached to the external surface, which can be dismembered in two independent layers, the internal one thinner (
<figureCitation box="[726,819,760,785]" captionStart="Figure 3–5" captionStartId="6.[160,225,1488,1511]" captionTargetBox="[172,1138,216,1454]" captionTargetId="figure-3@6.[163,1153,142,1457]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 3–5. Cocoon morphology of species of Sphecinae. 3, Sphex opacus: 3(a) internal capsule, with a last instar larva inside; 3(b) internal felt-like covering of the internal capsule; 3(c) external felt-like covering of the internal capsule; 3(d) external capsule. 4, Isodontia costipennis: 4(a) external capsule; 4(b) internal capsule, with an adult wasp inside. 5, Prionyx thomae: 5(a) external capsule; 5(b) internal capsule." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6351765" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6351765/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="2940">Figure 3</figureCitation>
(b,c)); meconium deposited in the basal extremity.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
